<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-328-223  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 328 223.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Information Week  Feb 6 1989 n206 p10(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Automation will clean up the pits. (Chicago commodity exchanges)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Caldwell, Bruce; Layne, Richard.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Automated trading systems may be forced on the futures marketfollowing recent FBI investigations into illegal practices in the'open outcry' auction systems at the Chicago Board of Trade (CBOT)and Chicago Mercantile Exchange (CME).andP;  The CME formed a reviewpanel to look into ways of correcting floor trading abuses.andP;  Thepanel is supposedly leaning toward automation that will replacehand signals and scribbles on scraps of paper.andP;  An automatedsystem can correct future abuses by providing an electronic audittrail for every bid and offer.andP;  As the news of the scandal broke,the Commodity Futures Trading Commission (CFTC) approved CME's useof Globex, an automated trading system.andP;  Meanwhile, as automationcreeps ahead, traders are keeping one eye over their shoulders.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Chicago Board of Trade (automation)Chicago Mercantile Exchange (automation).andO;Topic:     FuturesCommoditiesAutomationAudit Trails.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>